Subject: [PATCH 3/4] Make transport migration claims precise: conceptual
 contract, execution non-guarantee, conformance suite from Phase 1
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Incorporates three corrections to the core:net/http migration story:

- Transport boundary is a conceptual contract (accept HTTP work, invoke
  dispatch, commit response, support shutdown), not a frozen four-procedure
  ABI; the private Transport shape stays minimal (data/serve/stop) and
  mutable until a second real adapter forces decisions, since the official
  package's server model (blocking, event loop, callbacks, workers) is
  unknown
- Execution model non-guarantee (normative): handlers are synchronous from
  the application perspective; the transport MAY run them on an I/O thread,
  worker, or managed context; no thread guarantee until the official
  adapter is prototyped. Records the open nbio question (slow sync handler
  can stall a per-thread loop) without choosing an answer prematurely
- Request/Response ownership (normative): framework-owned abstractions
  whose storage MAY be transport-owned views for the request lifetime;
  retention requires explicit copy — no mandatory full copies
- Testing split into contract suite (test transport), factory-parameterized
  transport conformance suite (every real adapter, from Phase 1 so the
  bootstrap backend cannot shape the design), and a small end-to-end suite
- New 'Future Migration to core:net/http' normative section with explicit
  migration success criteria; wording fixed to 'future official package'
  with no assumed release date, and 'controlled and application-transparent'
  instead of 'trivial'

